g 85. Dinomachus et. callipho: of these two, though they are often mentioned by Cicero (e.g. Off. iii 33, 119; Fin. v 8, 213 Ac. ii 45, 139) little else is known.

indolentiam: cf. iii 6, 12 n.

Diodorus of Tyre (Stob. Ecl. Phys. i 1, 29) was a pupil of the Peripatetic Critolaus (Or. i ιι, 45).

Aristonis‚ Pyrrhonis: ii 6, 15 n.

Erim: Erillus of Carthage was a pupil of Zeno (Diog. Laert. vii 166 ; Ac. ii 42, 129) ; he is frequently mentioned by Cicero (Fin. ii, 13, 43, etc.); for the spelling Erillus as against Herillus see Madvig’s

note on Fin. ii 11, 35. According to him the summum bonum was ἐπιστήμη (Diog. L. l.c.).

obtinere: i 12, 26 n.

explicata, ‘unambiguous'; for the ad- jectival use edd. quote Or. i 2, 4; pro Plane. 2, 5; Att. ix 7, 2.

Theophrastum: cf. 9, 2 5 above and Fin. v 5, 12 ‘Theoplirasti...liber in quo multum admodum fortunae datur.'

exaggerent: cf. 18, 51 n.

extulerunt: cf. ii 23, 54 n. on resti- terunt.

conterere, ‘disparage‚’ an unusual meaning; cf. Plaut. Poen. 557 ‘est domi quod edimus ne nos tam contemptim conteras)
